1 Overview of the Problem

In the ever-evolving e-commerce space, it is critical to understand market dynamics, consumer behaviour and trends. The Olist Brazil E-Commerce Public Dataset represents an invaluable resource for researchers and analysts seeking insight into the e-commerce industry over a specific period of time.

This dataset was obtained from the Kaggle website (Brazilian E-Commerce Public Dataset by Olist). The license code for the dataset is: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0. The dataset has information of 100k orders from 2016 to 2018 made at multiple marketplaces in Brazil. Its features allows viewing an order from multiple dimensions: from order status, price, payment and freight performance to customer location, product attributes and finally reviews written by customers.

This dataset was chosen because it provides a comprehensive snapshot of the Brazilian e-commerce sector over a specific period of time. Not only does it reflect the developments and challenges facing the Brazilian e-commerce sector, but it also provides a rich source of information for those interested in studying consumer preferences, supply chain operations, and the booming industry. Our target is to predict the customer review score (1-5) from relevant information about each purchase.

2 Dataset Description

It contains nine subsets of data, eight of which were then combined by R code. The combination was done mainly through column variables about IDs. After collation, the dataset has a total of 23 attributes and 118146 Rows. The attributes are as follows:

3 Initial Data Analysis & Feature Engineering

The full dataset is combined from the 8 smaller datasets detailing various aspects of the purchases made at Olist. All unique id numbers and the geo-location of customers and sellers are removed from the dataset to ensure anonymity. All features that would appear along with the reviews are also removed, as we would not have such information when we would like to predict the review score.

# generate number of items per order, to used instead of the order_item_id
df_nitems_per_order = combined_trimmed %>%

Figure 3.3: Numerical feature distributions before scaling.

When plotting the distributions of all the numerical features (Figure 3.3), we can see some outliers that are noticeably further away from the other data points. For example, n > 20 items per order, payment value > 10000, and product weight > 35000 (g). These outliers, along with any unreasonable edge values such as 0 in number of items per order and 0 in product weight, are removed from our dataset. Figure 3.3 also shows right-tail skewed distribution in all numerical features excepted for the product name length. These variables are thus log-transformed with the equation \(\log (x + 1)\), in an attempt to make the features more normally distributed. The \(1\) is added to deal with any potential zeros in the feature values. For many machine learning algorithms, it is often beneficial to have the predictors on the same scale. Although this is not the case for our random forest model, the logistic regression model does require the features on the same scale. Therefore, the numerical features are standardized using a mean of 0 and unit standard deviations.

# remove rows with NA, and filter outliers and unreasonable values
df_final2_clean = df_final2 %>% remove_missing() %>% 
  filter(n_items_per_order < 19,
         n_items_per_order > 0,
         payment_value < 10000,
         price < 6000,
         product_name_length > 0,
         product_weight_g < 35000,
         product_weight_g > 0) %>%
  # all numerical variables apart from product_name_length are right tail skewed, log transform them
  mutate(across(num_cols[!num_cols == "product_name_length"], ~log(.+1))) %>% 
  # standardize numerical features, so that all features are on the same scale
  mutate(across(num_cols, ~as.vector(scale(.))))

# see boxplot of numerical variables of df2 (standardized log(x+1))
df_final2_clean %>% select(num_cols) %>%

4.1 Logistic Regression

The original review score in the dataset has 5 classes, which were integers from 1 to 5. A logistic regression is usually used in binary classification. Here we have generated a binary review score variable where 1 represents good reviews (review score 4 and 5) and 0 represents bad reviews (review score 1, 2 and 3). In the following parts, we attempt to perform classification using multiple variations of a logistic regression model, on both the original ordinal review score (1-5) and the binary review score (0 and 1).

# select only numerical columns and review score as numeric, plot correlation matrix
correlations <- cor(df_final2_clean %>% select(num_cols, review_score) %>% mutate(across(review_score, as.numeric)))
corrplot(correlations, method="square", tl.cex=0.8, title = "Correlation Between Numerical Attributes and Target Variable", mar = c(0,0,2,0))

Figure 4.1: Correlation Plot

Through the correlation plot (Figure 4.1), we can see that only the number of items per order (n_item_per_order) and the number of days it took for the order to reach customers (real_delivered_days) seem to have relatively significant impact on the review score. The price is highly correlated to the payment value and the product weight, and the product weight seems to be highly correlated with the product volume. The multicollinearity can have a negative impact on the model performance, however, for consistency between the different models we have kept all the independent variables in the logistic regression model.

4.1.1 Multinominal Classification

The multinom function from the nnet package is then used for fitting the model because it can be used to process multi-class classification data. The function utilises neural network to compute the probability of belonging to each class. Dummy-variables are created for each of the (n-1) categories in the categorical features.

# multi-class logistic regression classification using nnet package
regr_logistic <- nnet::multinom(review_score ~ ., data = cbind(X_train_dummied, review_score = y_train))

save(regr_logistic, file = "data/regr_logistic.RData")
load(file = "data/regr_logistic.RData")

#train set prediction

#train set prediction, class probabilities

#test set prediction
pre_test_logistic <- predict(regr_logistic, newdata = X_test_dummied, type = "class")
#test set prediction, class probabilities
pre_test_logistic_prob <- predict(regr_logistic, newdata = X_test_dummied, type = "prob")

confmat_logit_train = confusionMatrix(pre_train_logistic, y_train)

conf_mats[["logit"]] = confmat_logit_test

4.1.2 Binary Classification

The glm function is commonly used to fit logistic regression models in binary classification problems. The function is very powerful and highly versatile through the many choices of the family type. In the following model, we use the previously generated binary review score as our target prediction variable.

# generate binary response variable, good reviews (4-5) = 1, bad reviews (1-3) = 0
y_binary = ifelse(as.numeric(y) >= 4, 1, 0) %>% as.factor()

# split into train and test set
y_train_binary = y_binary[inTrain]
y_test_binary = y_binary[-inTrain]
# glimpse(y_train_binary)

# binary logistic regression
regr_logistic_binary <- glm(binary_review_score ~ ., data = cbind(X_train_dummied, binary_review_score = y_train_binary), family = binomial(link = "logit"))

#train set prediction class probabilities
pre_train_logistic_binary <- predict(regr_logistic_binary, newdata = X_train_dummied, type = "response")

#test set prediction class probabilities
pre_test_logistic_binary <- predict(regr_logistic_binary, newdata = X_test_dummied, type = "response")

# Convert prediction probability to binary (0 or 1)
predicted_train_binary <- ifelse(pre_train_logistic_binary > 0.5, 1, 0) %>% as.factor()
predicted_test_binary <- ifelse(pre_test_logistic_binary > 0.5, 1, 0) %>% as.factor()

# train set confusion matrix (binary response)
confmat_logit_train_binary = confusionMatrix(predicted_train_binary, y_train_binary, positive = "1")
confmat_logit_test_binary = confusionMatrix(predicted_test_binary, y_test_binary, positive = "1")
# performance metrics on test set(binary response)
# confmat_logit_test_binary
accuracy_binary = confmat_logit_test_binary$overall[["Accuracy"]]

#ROC
roc_train_logistic_binary <- multiclass.roc(y_train, pre_train_logistic_binary)
roc_test_logistic_binary <- multiclass.roc(y_test, pre_test_logistic_binary)

##auc train
auc_train_binary = roc_train_logistic_binary[["auc"]]
#auc test
auc_test_binary = roc_test_logistic_binary[["auc"]]

On the basis of glm functions, the binary classification on the review score results in a much higher accuracy of 0.78, which is expected, as logistic regression is more suitable for binary classification problems. The AUC is slightly increased to 0.64.

4.1.3 Hyperparameter Tuning

Using the binary review score as the target variable, we then tune the hyperparameters of the logistic regression model. A cross-validated grid search is performed over alpha values of 0 to 1 by steps of 0.1 and lambda values of 0.001 to 1 by 0.01. The best parameter values are found to be alpha = 0.6 and lambda = 0.001. The final model is then trained using the best parameters.

Converting to binary data may not be a good choice, as it differs from the original dataset. This may lead to losing information from the dataset and the categories are not balanced. Ordinal logistic regression may be a more suitable model for our research question.

4.2 \(k\)-Nearest Neighbours (KNN)

# knn using only payment type as a categorical predictor
# one-hot encoding of payment_type column
data_norm <- df_final2_clean %>% 
  select(-c('order_status', 'customer_state', 'seller_state'))

data_oneH <- select(dummy_cols(data_norm, select_columns = 'payment_type'), -'payment_type')
train_knn <- data_oneH[inTrain, ]
test_knn <- data_oneH[-inTrain, ]

We chose the k-NN model to predict this dataset because k-NN is a non-parametric and supervised model that could be applied to both classification and regression problems. Most of the preprocessing is finished in the previous procedure. There are three feature engineering techniques applied that aim to adjust the dataset, adapting the characteristics of the k-NN model.

Feature selection. Four attributes are dropped since the results from testing the model appeal that these attributes may have no contribution to the model performance, and also transformed the dataset into high dimensions after using one-hot encoding.

Normalization. All of the numerical data are normalized to a fixed range of zero to one because the units will significantly affect the distance, which is one of the essential hyperparameters.

One-hot encoding. All nominal data are transformed into dummy variables through one-hot encoding. There are two reasons: (a) the k-NN model needs numerical values to calculate the distances; (b) the new dataset, after executing one-hot encoding, may not cause high dimensionality.

Oversampling or Undersampling. Since the classes in this dataset are highly imbalanced in sample amount, all the predictive results tend toward class 5. This situation may worsen the performance of k-NN because most of the neighbours around one observation are more likely to belong to the majority classes. We tried to increase the number of samples for minority groups, such as class 2 and 3, by applying functions like SMOTE or mwmote, or decrease the number of samples for majority groups, such as class 5; however, these attempts did not improve the model results.

4.2.1 Hyperparameter Tuning

# not evaluated when compiling
k_value = 1
for (i in 1:20){
  pred <- knn(train = train_knn[,-1], test = test_knn[,-1], train_knn$review_score, k = i)
  k_value[i] <- 100 * sum(pred == test_knn$review_score) / length(test_knn$review_score)
  k = i
  cat(k,'=',k_value[i],'')
}
# save(k_value, file = "data/k_value.RData")

There are two most significant hyperparameters for the k-NN model: k value and distance. The k value is the number of neighbours around a sample point. A larger k value may cause underfitting, smooth decision boundary and loss of data information; a smaller k value may lead to overfitting, rough decision boundary and sensitivity to noise points. Distance measures the distance between two observations. Different distances determine different samples are selected as nearest neighbours. Some common distance metrics are Euclidean distance, Manhattan distance, Mahalanobis distance and Hamming distance.

# presaved computed knn data
load(file = "data/k_value.RData")
plot(k_value, type = "b", xlab = "K Value", ylab = "Accuracy level (%)", main = "Change of Accuracy with K values")

Figure 4.2: Change of knn model prediction accuracy with k values.

The best hyperparameters we have are when the k-value equals to 15 and Euclidean distance with 0.58 accuracy, where the accuracy stops to increase. (Figure 4.2)

pred_prob <- knn3Train(train = train_knn[, -1], test = test_knn[, -1], cl = train_knn$review_score, k = 15, prob = TRUE)

conf_mats[["knn"]] = confusionMatrix(pred, test_knn$review_score)

# Compute precision, recall and F1-score.
conM <- table(test_knn[, 'review_score'], pred)
prec <- numeric(nrow(conM))
recall <- numeric(nrow(conM))
f1 <- numeric(nrow(conM))

for(i in 1:nrow(conM)){
  tp <- conM[i, i]
  fp <- sum(conM[-i, i])
  fn <- sum(conM[i, -i])
  tn <- sum(conM) - tp - fp - fn
  
  prec[i] <- tp / (tp + fp)
  recall[i] <- tp / (tp + fn)
  f1[i] <- 2 * (prec[i] * recall[i]) / (prec[i] + recall[i])
}

# Create table.
table <- data.frame(Class = 1:nrow(conM),
                    Precision = prec,
                    Recall = recall,
                    F1_Score = f1)
table %>% round(2) %>% 
  rename(`F1 Score` = "F1_Score") %>% 
  kbl(caption = "Performance metrics for KNN (k = 15) model, per review score class basis.",
      format = "html", 
      booktabs = TRUE, 
      escape = TRUE) %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("condensed", "striped", "hover"),
                position = "center")

4.2.3 Discussion

The k-NN model may be improved by executing better approaches for choosing features and solving imbalance-class problems. This procedure is necessary since k-NN is sensitive to outliers, imbalanced-class data and irrelevant attributes. Reducing computational complexity is a significant problem that needs to be considered when using k-NN. Techniques such as KD-trees, fast approximate similarity search and locality-sensitive hashing may be beneficial.

4.3.2 Hyperparameter Tuning

# parameter range
ntree_values <- c(30, 40, 50)  # number of trees
mtry_values <- c(2, 3)         # number of randomly selected features

best_model <- NULL
highest_accuracy <- 0
best_ntree <- NULL
best_mtry <- NULL

# iterate parameters
for (ntree in ntree_values) {
  for (mtry in mtry_values) {
    
    rf_model <- ranger(x = X_train_new, y = y_train_new, ntree = ntree, mtry = mtry)
    rf_predict <- predict(rf_model, X_test)$predictions
    
    # accuracy
    accuracy <- round(sum(rf_predict == y_test) / nrow(X_test), 2)
    
    # If is best model, update the best model and  accuracy
    if (accuracy > highest_accuracy) {
      highest_accuracy <- accuracy
      best_model <- rf_model
      best_ntree <- ntree
      best_mtry <- mtry
    }
    
    # cat(paste("ntree:", ntree, "; mtry:", mtry, "; accuracy:", accuracy, "\n"))
  }
}

This phenomenon may be related to data augmentation performed by the SMOTE technique, which balances the distribution of categories in the dataset but potentially introduces noise when generating new samples, leading to overlearning of noise by the model. Subsequent consideration needs to be given to trying other data enhancement techniques, introducing regularisation methods, using boosting algorithms and other integrated strategies to improve the generalisation ability of the model.

4.4 Nave Bayes

The Nave Bayes model is widely employed in multiclass classification problems due to its simple modelling assumptions and lack of hyperparameters. Moreover, it is computationally efficient and adept at handling high-dimensional datasets. Upon importing and reviewing the dataset, a significant issue arises: the distribution of categories within the dataset is highly imbalanced. Notably, there are over 50,000 data instances belonging to category 5, whereas category 2 comprises only around 3,800 instances. This data characteristic poses a substantial challenge to subsequent model training. Directly applying the model risks biasing predictions toward category 5. To mitigate this, an initial step involves undersampling the dataset, ensuring a balanced representation of categories within both the training and test sets.

# 
under_sampled_data <- df_final2_clean %>%
                      group_by(review_score) %>%
                      sample_n(size = 2000, replace = FALSE)

labels <- under_sampled_data$review_score
features <- under_sampled_data[, -which(names(under_sampled_data) == "review_score")]


inTrain <- createDataPartition(labels, p = 0.8)[[1]]

x_train <- features[inTrain, ]
x_test <- features[-inTrain, ]
y_train <- labels[inTrain]
y_test <- labels[-inTrain]
y_train_fac <- factor(y_train)
y_test_fac <- factor(y_test)

naive_mod <- naive_bayes(y_train_fac ~ ., data = x_train)

naive_train_pre <- predict(naive_mod, newdata = x_train)
confusion_train <- confusionMatrix(naive_train_pre, y_train_fac)
accuracy_train <- confusion_train$overall["Accuracy"]

naive_pre <- predict(naive_mod, newdata = x_test)
naive_pre_prob <- predict(naive_mod, newdata = x_test, type = "prob")
confusion <- confusionMatrix(naive_pre, y_test_fac)
accuracy_test <- confusion$overall["Accuracy"]
nb_auc = multiclass.roc(y_test_fac, naive_pre_prob) %>% auc()

# save performance metrics to use later in conclusion
perform_df$Accuracy[perform_df$Model == "Nave Bayes"] = accuracy_test
perform_df$AUC[perform_df$Model == "Nave Bayes"] = nb_auc
conf_mats[["nb"]] = confusion

# print(paste("Accuracy on training set (2 d.p.s):", round(accuracy_train, 2), "\n"))
# print(paste("Accuracy on test set (2 d.p.s):", round(accuracy_test, 3)))

Following this balanced dataset split, the Nave Bayes model is constructed using the naive_bayes() function from the naivebayes library in R. However, the model exhibits suboptimal performance, yielding an accuracy of 0.31 on the training set and a lower accuracy of 0.28 on the test set. Despite employing various techniques such as Lasso feature extraction, attempts to enhance model accuracy have proven unsuccessful. Further investigation is imperative to comprehend the precise reasons behind these limitations, warranting in-depth research and analysis.

roc_curve <- roc(y_test, as.numeric(naive_pre))

plot(roc_curve, main="ROC Curve", col="blue", lwd=2)

Figure 4.6: Confusion matrix of the Nave Bayes predictions on undersampled data.

The accuracy metrics reveal the suboptimal fit of the model to both the training and test sets. However, post-undersampling, the ROC curve (Figure 4.5) and confusion matrix heatmap (Figure 4.6) exhibit enhanced performance compared to the untreated dataset. This improvement signifies that while the models fit to the undersampled dataset remains modest, its predictions across categories are more balanced, avoiding a disproportionate tendency to classify data into category 5. The heatmap analysis indicates superior predictive accuracy for category 1, closely followed by category 2.

Nevertheless, a comprehensive exploration of the factors contributing to the plain Bayesian models lacklustre performance is imperative. This discrepancy could stem from inadequacies in the datasets preprocessing methods or, alternatively, from the inherent limitations of the plain Bayesian models assumptions. The latter, characterized by its simplistic assumption of feature column independence, may clash with the intricate interdependencies present in certain dataset features. This mismatch renders the plain Bayesian model ill-suited for precise predictions in this particular dataset. Further investigation is warranted to discern the precise sources of these challenges and refine the modelling approach accordingly.

6 Conclusion

In this classification problem, the overall predictive results of the four models are not ideal. The reason for poor performance may be the methods of data preprocessing and insufficient analysis of attributes. The overall performance of the k-NN model is slightly better than others; however, its longer runtime needs to be considered. Although the random forest model works better in balancing trade-offs between multiple classes, its overfitting issue needs to be addressed. In addition, we made expansions and attempts in the modelling process, while they brought unsatisfactory outcomes. For instance, we expanded the logistic regression model, which is supposed to be used for binary classifications, to the multi-classification problem. We have also tried ordinal logistic regression, albeit it was not included in the report because it did not render better results.

We may research for improvements from at least two directions in the future work:

Model suitability: we may find more suitable models or apply integration techniques, such as the SVM model and bagging or boosting method, to improve the stability and performance of this problem.

Feature engineering: we may more carefully conduct an analysis of the dataset and extract the most correlated features to the target variable to reduce the influence of irrelevant attributes.

Appendix A - Data Dictionary

Attributes Data type Explanation
order_id Character order unique identifier
review_score Numeric Note ranging from 1 to 5 given by the customer on a satisfaction survey
order_status Character Reference to the order status (delivered, shipped, etc)
order_purchase_timestamp Datetime Shows the purchase timestamp
order_delivered_carrier_date Datetime Shows the order posting timestamp
order_delivered_customer_date Datetime Shows the actual order delivery date to the customer
order_estimated_delivery_date Datetime Shows the estimated delivery date that was informed to customer at the purchase moment
customer_state Character customer state
order_item_id Numeric sequential number identifying number of items included in the same order
price Numeric item price
freight_value Numeric item freight value item (if an order has more than one item the freight value is split between items)
seller_state Character seller state
product_name_length Numeric number of characters extracted from the product name
product_description_length Numeric number of characters extracted from the product description
product_photos_qty Numeric number of product published photos
product_weight_g Numeric product weight measured in grams
product_length_cm Numeric product length measured in centimeters
product_height_cm Numeric product height measured in centimeters
product_width_cm Numeric product width measured in centimeters
payment_type Character method of payment chosen by the customer
payment_installments Numeric number of installments chosen by the customer
payment_value Numeric transaction value
product_category_name_english Character category name in English
